<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="35" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="35">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Panops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Panops conspicuus" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conspicuus">Panops conspicuus</taxonomicName>
is recorded from arid regions of southwest Western Australia and Western Victoria. There is dramatic sexual dimorphism in both body colouration and shape in this species, with males very similar to species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Mesophysa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesophysa" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mesophysa</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Panops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Panops conspicuus" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conspicuus">Panops conspicuus</taxonomicName>
can be differentiated from other 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Panops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Panops" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Panops</taxonomicName>
species by the bright yellow postpronotal lobes, elongate mouthparts, yellow and brown colouration (female), and apilose eyes. Females of this species are similarly coloured to females of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Panops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Panops grossi" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grossi">Panops grossi</taxonomicName>
comb. n., a species which also displays dramatic sexual dimorphism.
</paragraph>
